blocks.name: stoweidlem1
blocks.content: Lemma for ~ stoweid . This lemma is used by Lemma 1 in [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 90; the key step uses Bernoulli's inequality ~ bernneq . (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem15
blocks.content: This lemma is used to prove the existence of a function ` p ` as in Lemma 1 from [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 90: ` p ` is in the subalgebra, such that 0 ≤ p ≤ 1, p_(t_0) = 0, and p > 0 on T - U. Here ` ( G `` I ) ` is used to represent p_(t_i) in the paper. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem20
blocks.content: If a set A of real functions from a common domain T is closed under the sum of two functions, then it is closed under the sum of a finite number of functions, indexed by G. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem23
blocks.content: This lemma is used to prove the existence of a function p_t as in the beginning of Lemma 1 [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 90: for all t in T - U, there exists a function p in the subalgebra, such that p_t ( t_0 ) = 0 , p_t ( t ) > 0, and 0 <= p_t <= 1. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem24
blocks.content: This lemma proves that for ` n ` sufficiently large, q_n( t ) > ( 1 - epsilon ), for all ` t ` in ` V ` : see Lemma 1 [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 90, (at the bottom of page 90). ` Q ` is used to represent q_n in the paper, ` N ` to represent ` n ` in the paper, ` K ` to represent ` k ` , ` D ` to represent δ, and ` E ` to represent ε. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem27
blocks.content: This lemma is used to prove the existence of a function p as in Lemma 1 [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 90: p is in the subalgebra, such that 0 <= p <= 1, p_(t_0) = 0, and p > 0 on T - U. Here ` ( q `` i ) ` is used to represent p_(t_i) in the paper. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem31
blocks.content: This lemma is used to prove that there exists a function x as in the proof of Lemma 2 in [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 91: assuming that ` R ` is a finite subset of ` V ` , ` x ` indexes a finite set of functions in the subalgebra (of the Stone Weierstrass theorem), such that for all ` i ` ranging in the finite indexing set, 0 ≤ x_i ≤ 1, x_i < ε / m on V(t_i), and x_i > 1 - ε / m on ` B ` . Here M is used to represent m in the paper, ` E ` is used to represent ε in the paper, v_i is used to represent V(t_i). (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem35
blocks.content: This lemma is used to prove the existence of a function p as in Lemma 1 of [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 90: p is in the subalgebra, such that 0 <= p <= 1, p_(t_0) = 0, and p > 0 on T - U. Here ` ( q `` i ) ` is used to represent p_(t_i) in the paper. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

  -| wnf(s2, w0)
  -| wnf(s4, w0)
  -| wnf(s5, w0)
  -| wceq(c0, crab(s5, c3, wa(wceq(cfv(cv(s5), c4), nat0), wral(s2, c1, wa(wbr(nat0, cle, cfv(cv(s5), cv(s2))), wbr(cfv(cv(s5), cv(s2)), cle, nat1))))))

blocks.name: stoweidlem36
blocks.content: This lemma is used to prove the existence of a function p_t as in Lemma 1 of [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 90 (at the beginning of Lemma 1): for all t in T - U, there exists a function p in the subalgebra, such that p_t ( t_0 ) = 0 , p_t ( t ) > 0, and 0 <= p_t <= 1. Z is used for t_0 , S is used for t e. T - U , h is used for p_t . G is used for (h_t)^2 and the final h is a normalized version of G ( divided by its norm, see the variable N ). (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem37
blocks.content: This lemma is used to prove the existence of a function p as in Lemma 1 of [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 90: p is in the subalgebra, such that 0 <= p <= 1, p_(t_0) = 0, and p > 0 on T - U. Z is used for t_0, P is used for p, ` ( G `` i ) ` is used for p_(t_i). (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem39
blocks.content: This lemma is used to prove that there exists a function x as in the proof of Lemma 2 in [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 91: assuming that ` r ` is a finite subset of ` W ` , ` x ` indexes a finite set of functions in the subalgebra (of the Stone Weierstrass theorem), such that for all i ranging in the finite indexing set, 0 ≤ x_i ≤ 1, x_i < ε / m on V(t_i), and x_i > 1 - ε / m on ` B ` . Here ` D ` is used to represent A in the paper's Lemma 2 (because ` A ` is used for the subalgebra), ` M ` is used to represent m in the paper, ` E ` is used to represent ε, and v_i is used to represent V(t_i). ` W ` is just a local definition, used to shorten statements. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem40
blocks.content: This lemma proves that q_n is in the subalgebra, as in the proof of Lemma 1 in [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 90. Q is used to represent q_n in the paper, N is used to represent n in the paper, and M is used to represent k^n in the paper. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)
blocks.origin:

  -| wnfc(s0, c2)

blocks.name: stoweidlem41
blocks.content: This lemma is used to prove that there exists x as in Lemma 1 of [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 90: 0 <= x(t) <= 1 for all t in T, x(t) < epsilon for all t in V, x(t) > 1 - epsilon for all t in T \ U. Here we prove the very last step of the proof of Lemma 1: "The result follows from taking x = 1 - q_n". Here ` E ` is used to represent ε in the paper, and ` y ` to represent q_n in the paper. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.content: This lemma is used to prove that ` x ` built as in Lemma 2 of [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 91, is such that x > 1 - ε on B. Here ` X ` is used to represent ` x ` in the paper, and E is used to represent ε in the paper. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem43
blocks.content: This lemma is used to prove the existence of a function p_t as in Lemma 1 of [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 90 (at the beginning of Lemma 1): for all t in T - U, there exists a function p_t in the subalgebra, such that p_t( t_0 ) = 0 , p_t ( t ) > 0, and 0 <= p_t <= 1. Hera Z is used for t_0 , S is used for t e. T - U , h is used for p_t. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem44
blocks.content: This lemma is used to prove the existence of a function p as in Lemma 1 of [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 90: p is in the subalgebra, such that 0 <= p <= 1, p_(t_0) = 0, and p > 0 on T - U. Z is used to represent t_0 in the paper. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)
blocks.origin:
thm stoweidlem44(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, setvar s3, setvar s4, setvar s5, setvar s6, setvar s7, class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, class c4, class c5, class c6, class c7, class c8, class c9, wff w0) {
  |- wi(w0, wrex(s0, c0, w3a(wral(s1, c1, wa(wbr(nat0, cle, cfv(cv(s0), cv(s1))), wbr(cfv(cv(s0), cv(s1)), cle, nat1))), wceq(cfv(cv(s0), c2), nat0), wral(s1, cdif(c1, c3), wbr(nat0, clt, cfv(cv(s0), cv(s1)))))))
  -| wnf(s2, w0)

blocks.name: stoweidlem45
blocks.content: This lemma proves that, given an appropriate ` K ` (in another theorem we prove such a ` K ` exists), there exists a function q_n as in the proof of Lemma 1 in [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 91 ( at the top of page 91): 0 <= q_n <= 1 , q_n < ε on T \ U, and q_n > 1 - ε on ` V ` . We use y to represent the final q_n in the paper (the one with n large enough), ` N ` to represent ` n ` in the paper, ` K ` to represent ` k ` , ` D ` to represent δ, ` E ` to represent ε, and ` P ` to represent ` p ` . (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem46
blocks.content: This lemma proves that sets U(t) as defined in Lemma 1 of [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 90, are a cover of T \ U. Using this lemma, in a later theorem we will prove that a finite subcover exists. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem49
blocks.content: There exists a function q_n as in the proof of Lemma 1 in [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 91 (at the top of page 91): 0 <= q_n <= 1 , q_n < ε on ` T \ U ` , and q_n > 1 - ε on ` V ` . Here y is used to represent the final q_n in the paper (the one with n large enough), ` N ` represents ` n ` in the paper, ` K ` represents ` k ` , ` D ` represents δ, ` E ` represents ε, and ` P ` represents ` p ` . (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem51
blocks.content: There exists a function x as in the proof of Lemma 2 in [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 91. Here ` D ` is used to represent ` A ` in the paper, because here ` A ` is used for the subalgebra of functions. ` E ` is used to represent ε in the paper. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem53
blocks.content: This lemma is used to prove the existence of a function p as in Lemma 1 of [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 90: p is in the subalgebra, such that 0 <= p <= 1, p_(t_0) = 0, and p > 0 on T - U. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem54
blocks.content: There exists a function ` x ` as in the proof of Lemma 2 in [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 91. Here ` D ` is used to represent ` A ` in the paper, because here ` A ` is used for the subalgebra of functions. ` E ` is used to represent ε in the paper. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem55
blocks.content: This lemma proves the existence of a function p as in the proof of Lemma 1 in [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 90: p is in the subalgebra, such that 0 <= p <= 1, p_(t_0) = 0, and p > 0 on T - U. Here Z is used to represent t_0 in the paper. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem56
blocks.content: This theorem proves Lemma 1 in [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 90. Here ` Z ` is used to represent t_0 in the paper, ` v ` is used to represent ` V ` in the paper, and ` e ` is used to represent ε. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem57
blocks.content: There exists a function x as in the proof of Lemma 2 in [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 91. In this theorem, it is proven the non-trivial case (the closed set D is nonempty). Here D is used to represent A in the paper, because the variable A is used for the subalgebra of functions. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem59
blocks.content: This lemma proves that there exists a function ` x ` as in the proof in [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 91, after Lemma 2: x_j is in the subalgebra, 0 <= x_j <= 1, x_j < ε / n on A_j (meaning A in the paper), x_j > 1 - \epslon / n on B_j. Here ` D ` is used to represent A in the paper (because A is used for the subalgebra of functions), ` E ` is used to represent ε. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem60
blocks.content: This lemma proves that there exists a function g as in the proof in [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 91 (this parte of the proof actually spans through pages 91-92): g is in the subalgebra, and for all ` t ` in ` T ` , there is a ` j ` such that (j-4/3)*ε < f(t) <= (j-1/3)*ε and (j-4/3)*ε < g(t) < (j+1/3)*ε. Here ` F ` is used to represent f in the paper, and ` E ` is used to represent ε. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem61
blocks.content: This lemma proves that there exists a function ` g ` as in the proof in [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 92: ` g ` is in the subalgebra, and for all ` t ` in ` T ` , abs( f(t) - g(t) ) < 2*ε. Here ` F ` is used to represent f in the paper, and ` E ` is used to represent ε. For this lemma there's the further assumption that the function ` F ` to be approximated is nonnegative (this assumption is removed in a later theorem). (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stoweidlem62
blocks.content: This theorem proves the Stone Weierstrass theorem for the non-trivial case in which T is nonempty. The proof follows [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 89 (through page 92). (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.) (Revised by AV, 13-Sep-2020.)

blocks.name: stoweid
blocks.content: This theorem proves the Stone-Weierstrass theorem for real-valued functions: let ` J ` be a compact topology on ` T ` , and ` C ` be the set of real continuous functions on ` T ` . Assume that ` A ` is a subalgebra of ` C ` (closed under addition and multiplication of functions) containing constant functions and discriminating points (if ` r ` and ` t ` are distinct points in ` T ` , then there exists a function ` h ` in ` A ` such that h(r) is distinct from h(t) ). Then, for any continuous function ` F ` and for any positive real ` E ` , there exists a function ` f ` in the subalgebra ` A ` , such that ` f ` approximates ` F ` up to ` E ` ( ` E ` represents the usual ε value). As a classical example, given any a, b reals, the closed interval ` T = [ a , b ] ` could be taken, along with the subalgebra ` A ` of real polynomials on ` T ` , and then use this theorem to easily prove that real polynomials are dense in the standard metric space of continuous functions on ` [ a , b ] ` . The proof and lemmas are written following [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 89 (through page 92). Some effort is put in avoiding the use of the axiom of choice. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)

blocks.name: stowei
blocks.content: This theorem proves the Stone-Weierstrass theorem for real-valued functions: let ` J ` be a compact topology on ` T ` , and ` C ` be the set of real continuous functions on ` T ` . Assume that ` A ` is a subalgebra of ` C ` (closed under addition and multiplication of functions) containing constant functions and discriminating points (if ` r ` and ` t ` are distinct points in ` T ` , then there exists a function ` h ` in ` A ` such that h(r) is distinct from h(t) ). Then, for any continuous function ` F ` and for any positive real ` E ` , there exists a function ` f ` in the subalgebra ` A ` , such that ` f ` approximates ` F ` up to ` E ` ( ` E ` represents the usual ε value). As a classical example, given any a, b reals, the closed interval ` T = [ a , b ] ` could be taken, along with the subalgebra ` A ` of real polynomials on ` T ` , and then use this theorem to easily prove that real polynomials are dense in the standard metric space of continuous functions on ` [ a , b ] ` . The proof and lemmas are written following [BrosowskiDeutsh] p. 89 (through page 92). Some effort is put in avoiding the use of the axiom of choice. The deduction version of this theorem is ~ stoweid : often times it will be better to use ~ stoweid in other proofs (but this version is probably easier to be read and understood). (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 20-Apr-2017.)
